The error message indicates that the application is unable to deserialize the `LocalDateTime` objects in the `schedule` field of the `Program` entity. This is because the Jackson library, which is used for JSON serialization/deserialization in RESTEasy, does not support Java 8 date/time types like `LocalDateTime` by default.

To fix this issue, you need to register the `jackson-datatype-jsr310` module with Jackson. This module provides support for Java 8 date/time types.

Here are the steps to resolve the issue:

1. Add the `jackson-datatype-jsr310` dependency to your project's `pom.xml` file:

```xml
<dependency>
    <groupId>com.fasterxml.jackson.datatype</groupId>
    <artifactId>jackson-datatype-jsr310</artifactId>
    <version>2.15.3</version>
</dependency>
```

2. Create a `JacksonConfig` class to register the `jackson-datatype-jsr310` module with Jackson:

```java
import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.ObjectMapper;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.datatype.jsr310.JavaTimeModule;
import jakarta.ws.rs.ext.ContextResolver;
import jakarta.ws.rs.ext.Provider;

@Provider
public class JacksonConfig implements ContextResolver<ObjectMapper> {

    private final ObjectMapper objectMapper;

    public JacksonConfig() {
        objectMapper = new ObjectMapper();
        objectMapper.registerModule(new JavaTimeModule());
    }

    @Override
    public ObjectMapper getContext(Class<?> type) {
        return objectMapper;
    }
}
```

3. Register the `JacksonConfig` class as a provider in your `Application` class:

```java
import jakarta.ws.rs.ApplicationPath;
import jakarta.ws.rs.core.Application;

import java.util.HashSet;
import java.util.Set;

@ApplicationPath("/api")
public class HelloApplication extends Application {

    @Override
    public Set<Class<?>> getClasses() {
        Set<Class<?>> classes = new HashSet<>();
        classes.add(JacksonConfig.class); // Register JacksonConfig
        // Add your resource classes here
        return classes;
    }
}
```

After making these changes, the application should be able to deserialize `LocalDateTime` objects correctly.

