here is @...\jeebackend\Services\ProgramService.java   :
package com.example.jeebackend.Services;

import com.example.jeebackend.Entities.Program;
import jakarta.ejb.Local;
import jakarta.ejb.Stateless;
import jakarta.persistence.EntityManager;
import jakarta.persistence.EntityManagerFactory;
import jakarta.persistence.Persistence;

import java.util.List;

@Stateless
@Local
public class ProgramService {

    EntityManagerFactory emf;

    EntityManager em;

    public ProgramService() {
        emf = Persistence.createEntityManagerFactory(&quot;jee&quot;);
        em = emf.createEntityManager();
    }

    public void createProgram(Program program) {
        try {
            em.getTransaction().begin();
            em.persist(program);
            em.getTransaction().commit();
        } catch (Exception e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }

    public Program findProgramById(Long id) {
        try {
            return em.find(Program.class, id);
        } catch (Exception e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
            return null;
        }
    }

    public List&lt;Program&gt; findAllPrograms() {
        try {
            return em.createQuery(&quot;SELECT p FROM Program p&quot;, Program.class).getResultList();
        } catch (Exception e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
            return null;
        }
    }

    public void updateProgram(long id, Program updatedProgram) {
        try {
            em.getTransaction().begin();
            Program existingProgram = em.find(Program.class, id);
            if (existingProgram != null) {
                existingProgram.setSchedules(updatedProgram.getSchedules());
                existingProgram.setSpeakers(updatedProgram.getSpeakers());
                existingProgram.setTopics(updatedProgram.getTopics());
                existingProgram.setImages(updatedProgram.getImages());
                existingProgram.setDetails(updatedProgram.getDetails());
                existingProgram.setEvent(updatedProgram.getEvent());
                em.merge(existingProgram);
            }
            em.getTransaction().commit();
        } catch (Exception e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }

    public void deleteProgramByID(long programId) {
        Program programToRemove = findProgramById(programId);
        if (programToRemove != null) {
            try {
                em.getTransaction().begin();
                em.remove(programToRemove);
                em.getTransaction().commit();
            } catch (Exception e) {
                e.printStackTrace();
            }
        }
    }
}

Based on the `ProgramService` class, the `updateProgram` method seems to be implemented correctly. It retrieves the existing `Program` entity from the database using the provided `id`, updates its fields with the values from the `updatedProgram` object, and then merges the updated entity back into the database.

However, there's a potential issue with the way you're handling the `EntityManager` and `EntityManagerFactory` instances. It's generally recommended to use dependency injection or a context-aware approach to manage these instances, rather than creating them directly in the service class.

Here's what you can do:

1. In your `ApiReactProgram` class, ensure that the resource method for handling the PUT request is correctly mapped to the appropriate URL pattern (`/api/programs/{id}`). Also, make sure that the method is annotated with `@PutMapping` or `@RequestMapping(method = RequestMethod.PUT)`.

2. In the resource method, retrieve the `id` parameter from the URL path using `@PathVariable` annotation, and pass it along with the `updatedProgram` object (retrieved from the request body) to the `updateProgram` method of `ProgramService`.

3. Consider refactoring the `ProgramService` class to use dependency injection or a context-aware approach for managing the `EntityManager` and `EntityManagerFactory` instances. This will ensure proper lifecycle management and thread safety.

Here's an example of how you can refactor the `ProgramService` class to use dependency injection with CDI (Context and Dependency Injection):

```java
import jakarta.ejb.Stateless;
import jakarta.persistence.EntityManager;
import jakarta.persistence.PersistenceContext;

@Stateless
public class ProgramService {

    @PersistenceContext(unitName = "jee")
    private EntityManager em;

    public void createProgram(Program program) {
        em.persist(program);
    }

    public Program findProgramById(Long id) {
        return em.find(Program.class, id);
    }

    public List<Program> findAllPrograms() {
        return em.createQuery("SELECT p FROM Program p", Program.class).getResultList();
    }

    public void updateProgram(long id, Program updatedProgram) {
        Program existingProgram = em.find(Program.class, id);
        if (existingProgram != null) {
            existingProgram.setSchedules(updatedProgram.getSchedules());
            existingProgram.setSpeakers(updatedProgram.getSpeakers());
            existingProgram.setTopics(updatedProgram.getTopics());
            existingProgram.setImages(updatedProgram.getImages());
            existingProgram.setDetails(updatedProgram.getDetails());
            existingProgram.setEvent(updatedProgram.getEvent());
            em.merge(existingProgram);
        }
    }

    public void deleteProgramByID(long programId) {
        Program programToRemove = findProgramById(programId);
        if (programToRemove != null) {
            em.remove(programToRemove);
        }
    }
}
```

In this refactored version, the `EntityManager` instance is injected using the `@PersistenceContext` annotation, and the transaction management is handled by the container (application server or EJB container).

4. If you're still getting a 404 Not Found error, double-check that the `id` you're using in the URL (`http://localhost:8080/Jee-Backend-1.0-SNAPSHOT/api/programs/{1}`) matches an existing program in your database.

After making these changes, try sending the PUT request again, and it should work as expected.

