The error message `Text '2024-09-19 10:00:00.000000' could not be parsed at index 10` indicates that Jackson is having trouble deserializing the `LocalDateTime` values in your `Program` entity.

The issue seems to be with the format of the date-time string being parsed. By default, Jackson expects date-time strings in the ISO-8601 format (e.g., `2023-04-20T10:30:00`). However, the string `2024-09-19 10:00:00.000000` is not in this format, which is causing the parsing error.

To fix this issue, you have a few options:

1. **Update the date-time format in your database**: If possible, update the format of the date-time values in your database to match the ISO-8601 format. This way, Jackson will be able to parse the values correctly without any additional configuration.

2. **Configure Jackson's date-time deserialization**: If you cannot change the format in the database, you can configure Jackson to use a custom date-time format for deserialization. You can do this by registering a custom `DateTimeDeserializer` with Jackson. Here's an example:

```java
import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.DeserializationFeature;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.ObjectMapper;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.module.SimpleModule;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.datatype.jsr310.deser.LocalDateTimeDeserializer;

// ...

ObjectMapper objectMapper = new ObjectMapper();
objectMapper.configure(DeserializationFeature.FAIL_ON_UNKNOWN_PROPERTIES, false);

SimpleModule module = new SimpleModule();
module.addDeserializer(LocalDateTime.class, new LocalDateTimeDeserializer(DateTimeFormatter.ofPattern("yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm:ss.SSSSSS")));
objectMapper.registerModule(module);
```

In this example, we create a custom `ObjectMapper` and register a `LocalDateTimeDeserializer` with a custom date-time format pattern (`yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm:ss.SSSSSS`) that matches the format in your database.

3. **Use a different date-time representation**: Instead of using `LocalDateTime`, you could consider using a different date-time representation that Jackson can parse more easily, such as a Unix timestamp or an ISO-8601 string. This approach would require changes to your data model and database schema.

Whichever approach you choose, make sure to apply the changes consistently throughout your application to avoid further deserialization issues.

