import javax.ws.rs.Consumes;
import javax.ws.rs.POST;
import javax.ws.rs.Path;
import javax.ws.rs.Produces;
import javax.ws.rs.core.MediaType;
import javax.ws.rs.core.Response;

@Path("/api/users")
public class UserResource {

    @POST
    @Consumes(MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON)
    @Produces(MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON)
    public Response createUser(User user) {
        // Perform validation and business logic
        if (user.getName() == null || user.getName().isEmpty()) {
            return Response.status(Response.Status.BAD_REQUEST)
                    .entity("Name is required")
                    .build();
        }

        // Save the user to the database or perform other operations
        User savedUser = userService.saveUser(user);

        return Response.status(Response.Status.CREATED)
                .entity(savedUser)
                .build();
    }
}
```

In this example, we have a `UserResource` class with a `createUser` method annotated with `@POST`. The `@Path("/api/users")` annotation defines the base URI for this resource.

The `@Consumes(MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON)` annotation specifies that the method can consume JSON data in the request body.

The `@Produces(MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON)` annotation specifies that the method will produce JSON data in the response body.

The `createUser` method takes a `User` object as input, which is automatically deserialized from the JSON request body by JAX-RS.

Inside the method, you can perform validation and business logic. In this example, we check if the `name` field of the `User` object is null or empty. If it is, we return a `Response` with a `BAD_REQUEST` status code and an error message.

If the validation passes, you can save the user to the database or perform other operations. In this example, we call a `userService.saveUser(user)` method and store the saved user in the `savedUser` variable.

Finally, we return a `Response` with a `CREATED` status code and the `savedUser` object as the response entity.

