The issue you're facing is likely due to the way you're handling the `createdAt` and `updatedAt` fields in your `Remark` entity. The `LocalDateTime` class is not a serializable type, which means that it cannot be directly converted to and from JSON format.

To fix this issue, you can use a custom JSON serializer/deserializer for the `LocalDateTime` fields, or you can convert the `LocalDateTime` values to a string format that can be easily serialized and deserialized.

Here's an example of how you can modify your `Remark` entity to use a string representation of the `LocalDateTime` fields:

```java
import com.fasterxml.jackson.annotation.JsonFormat;

@Entity
@Table(name = "remarks")
public class Remark {
    // ... other fields ...

    @JsonFormat(pattern = "yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH:mm:ss")
    @Column(name = "created_at", nullable = false)
    private String createdAt;

    @JsonFormat(pattern = "yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH:mm:ss")
    @Column(name = "updated_at")
    private String updatedAt;

    // ... other fields and methods ...
}
```

In this modified version, the `createdAt` and `updatedAt` fields are now of type `String`, and the `@JsonFormat` annotation is used to specify the date-time format for serialization and deserialization.

You'll also need to modify the constructor and getter/setter methods for these fields to handle the string representation:

```java
public Remark(String description, String priority,
              String createdAt, String updatedAt,
              String status, RemarkType type, User user) {
    this.description = description;
    this.priority = priority;
    this.createdAt = createdAt;
    this.updatedAt = updatedAt;
    this.status = status;
    this.type = type;
    this.user = user;
}

// Getters and setters
public String getCreatedAt() {
    return createdAt;
}

public void setCreatedAt(String createdAt) {
    this.createdAt = createdAt;
}

public String getUpdatedAt() {
    return updatedAt;
}

public void setUpdatedAt(String updatedAt) {
    this.updatedAt = updatedAt;
}
```

With these changes, your `Remark` entity should be able to handle the JSON serialization and deserialization correctly.

Additionally, make sure that your `RemarkService` and `ApiReactRemark` classes are correctly handling the string representation of the `createdAt` and `updatedAt` fields when creating or updating a `Remark` instance.

Since you already have the necessary configurations for serializing and deserializing `LocalDateTime` objects, the issue might be related to the way you're handling the request body in your `ApiReactRemark` class.

In your `createRemark` method, you're directly trying to create a `Remark` instance from the request body. However, the request body might not contain all the required fields, such as `createdAt` and `updatedAt`, which are expected to be set by the server-side logic.

Here's how you can modify your `createRemark` method to handle the request body correctly:

```java
@POST
public Response createRemark(Remark remark) {
    String token = getJwtTokenFromRequest(httpServletRequest);
    if (token != null && authenticationService.validateToken(token)) {
        // Check if the user has the required role (e.g., "ADMIN")
        String role = authenticationService.getRoleFromToken(token);
        if (role.equals("ADMIN")) {
            String userEmail = authenticationService.getEmailFromToken(token);
            User user = userService.findByEmail(userEmail);

            // Create a new Remark instance with the provided fields
            Remark newRemark = new Remark();
            newRemark.setDescription(remark.getDescription());
            newRemark.setPriority(remark.getPriority());
            newRemark.setStatus(remark.getStatus());
            newRemark.setType(remark.getType());

            // Set the user and the current date-time for createdAt and updatedAt
            newRemark.setUser(user);
            LocalDateTime now = LocalDateTime.now();
            newRemark.setCreatedAt(now);
            newRemark.setUpdatedAt(now);

            remarkService.registerRemark(user, newRemark);
            return Response.status(Response.Status.CREATED).build();
        } else {
            return Response.status(Response.Status.FORBIDDEN).build();
        }
    } else {
        return Response.status(Response.Status.UNAUTHORIZED).build();
    }
}
```

In this modified version, we create a new `Remark` instance (`newRemark`) and set the fields from the request body (`remark.getDescription()`, `remark.getPriority()`, `remark.getStatus()`, `remark.getType()`). Then, we set the `user` field with the authenticated user, and set the `createdAt` and `updatedAt` fields with the current date-time using `LocalDateTime.now()`.

Finally, we pass the `newRemark` instance to the `remarkService.registerRemark` method.

By separating the creation of the `Remark` instance from the request body, you ensure that the required fields (`createdAt`, `updatedAt`, and `user`) are set correctly on the server-side.

