Ah, I see. Based on the error logs you provided earlier, it seems that you are using the H2 database for your application. In that case, we can take a different approach to handle the `createdAt` and `updatedAt` columns.

H2 provides a built-in function `CURRENT_TIMESTAMP` that can be used to retrieve the current date and time. We can leverage this function to set the default values for `createdAt` and `updatedAt` columns directly in the database schema.

Here's how you can update the `Remark` entity class to work with H2:

```java
package com.example.jeebackend.Entities;

import com.fasterxml.jackson.annotation.JsonProperty;
import jakarta.persistence.*;
import java.time.LocalDateTime;

@Entity
@Table(name = "remarks")
public class Remark {

    @Id
    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
    @Column(name = "remark_id", nullable = false)
    @JsonProperty("remark_id")
    private Long id;

    @Column(name = "remark_text", nullable = false)
    private String description;

    @Column(name = "priority")
    private String priority;

    @Column(name = "created_at", nullable = false, columnDefinition = "TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP")
    private LocalDateTime createdAt;

    @Column(name = "updated_at", nullable = false, columnDefinition = "TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP ON UPDATE CURRENT_TIMESTAMP")
    private LocalDateTime updatedAt;

    @Column(name = "status")
    private String status;

    @Enumerated(EnumType.STRING)
    private RemarkType type;

    @ManyToOne
    @JoinColumn(name = "user_id", nullable = false)
    private User user;

    // Constructors, getters, and setters...
}
```

In this updated code:

1. The `createdAt` column is defined with `nullable = false` and `columnDefinition = "TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP"`. This will ensure that the column cannot be null, and if no value is provided during insertion, H2 will automatically set the current timestamp as the default value.

2. The `updatedAt` column is defined with `nullable = false` and `columnDefinition = "TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP ON UPDATE CURRENT_TIMESTAMP"`. This will ensure that the column cannot be null, and whenever the row is updated, H2 will automatically update the `updatedAt` column with the current timestamp.

With these changes, you should no longer encounter the "NULL not allowed for column 'CREATED_AT'" error when inserting new `Remark` instances into the database using H2.

